Reference for Yaqi Liao
To whom it may concern,
I have had the pleasure and privilege of tutoring Yaqi Liao in the final Design Studio grad
project of her bachelor’s degree in 2021.
Yaqi’s graduation project was a theatre on the water in Sydney Harbour. The initial
contextualisation incorporated studies of the theatre typology and buildings on the water
as well as critically siting their project in the harbour. Yaqi’s project immediately stood out
as she developed a highly intelligent and creative concept around a kinetic semi-
submerged theatre. Through technical analysis of kinetic and submarine structures and
inspired by the form and movement of jellyfish, Yaqi developed a theatre that “creates”
the entrance when needed and later “creates” the stage for underwater performances,
providing a unique experiential suspension and phenomenal transparency for both
audience and performers. The technical and poetic dimensions of this project are
extraordinary and demonstrate a courageous and creative attitude
Yaqi is an ambitious, intelligent, and talented student. Her graphic communication is
sophisticated, detailed, and seductive. Her design talent combines an analytical mindset
with an intuitive eye for the drama of innovative, inspirational, and poetic spaces. She
takes on board tutor feedback with an open-minded attitude and subsequently takes full
ownership and agency over her response to the feedback.
Yaqi has a solid work ethic: she is fully engaged and produces an amazing amount of work to
test ideas and keep the iterative momentum up. Her work shows a methodical, inquisitive and
engaged approach. She has a passionate, critical and inspiring personality and she would
contribute positively to any post-grad programme or workplace.
I recommend Yaqi without hesitation or reservation in her further academic pursuits as well as in
positions of practicing architecture
Kind regards
Thomas Stromberg
Cand.Arch. (The Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts, 2001)

To the Admissions Committee:
It is my pleasure to provide this letter of reference on behalf of Yaqi Liao. I worked directly with
Yaqi while she was an intern designer in our Shanghai Studio of which I am the Principal-in-
Charge. Over the period of time she was with our studio in 2021, about half a year, she was staffed
on some of our most important projects. Though an intern, Yaqi very quickly proved herself to be a
valuable and integral member of our design studio well beyond most interns in our firm.
One key aspect is her positive attitude, creative spirit, and thoroughness of delivering the work that
she was responsible. Yaqi also has a strong balance of design ability, artistic technique with
technical intuition. Her focus on learning is clear; she frequently asked good questions and
consistently scribes her findings in her notebook. And Yaqi reliably applies new information and
skills she acquires to whatever work she is immediately engaged.
Yaqi was a member of the team designing new office spaces in a headquarters building we had
designed for a young technology company in Shanghai. The process included understanding the
client’s demanding needs that changed frequently, which is common with headquarters projects.
Yet, Yaqi “never missed a beat” and kept up with the team through all the twists and turns. At each
iteration, maintaining high efficiency and focus on the project goals. From design to technical
documentation, she was a big part of this project’s success. This project is in construction now –
and the smoothness of this phase is a testament to Yaqi’s earlier contributions with the team.
Yaqi also had the opportunity to participate in a demanding competition project; a large, university
library building in Shanghai. Yaqi quickly found a role on the team taking on important work
developing the building facade with myself. I found her ability to contribute highly relevant ideas
impressive given her experience level. Even more importantly, she was highly effective working
with other team members developing one another’s ideas to make meaningful contributions to the
overall project design. I’m always proud to share how many of ideas that she was involved ended
up in the project’s final scheme; a testament to our collaborative working methods.
